(1298, 526, '_solution', '<p>Creating a warm welcome email for new customers is an excellent way to start off the onboarding journey for them. By directing customers to the preference center, you can offer them control over their experience, while also gathering valuable data for future communications.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step-by-step Guide</h5>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">1</span> This challenge, similar to the previous one, consists of multiple components. You need to create several elements: a new field to capture the launch date, a welcome email, a dynamic list to identify those eligible to receive the welcome email, a landing page with a form for customers to select their role, and an Engagement Studio program that sends the welcome email. The program will then send onboarding emails tailored to the selected role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Start by creating a new field called <strong>Account Launch Date</strong> in the Prospect object to capture the launch date. Import the sample dataset after creating the new field.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-account-launch-date.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-account-launch-date.png\" alt=\"Account Launch Date Field\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n\r\n<p>You also need to create a field to save the customer\'s role. Name this field <strong>Role</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-role.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-role.png\" alt=\"Role Field\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n\r\n[guide id=\"114\" status=\"closed\"]\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">2</span> Next, create your welcome email template.</p>\r\n\r\n[guide id=\"59\" status=\"closed\"]\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">3</span> Then, create the form and the landing page. If you checked the landing preview in the resources section, you will notice that the form looks different compared to the ones you have created before. The landing page template includes custom CSS that hides default radio buttons and allows you to display images. For images that appear on the form, add them directly to the form.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-form.gif\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-form.gif\" alt=\"Form Creation\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n\r\n[guide id=\"93\" status=\"closed\"]\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">4</span> In the final step, create the Engagement Studio program. For the recipient list, create a dynamic list where the customer\'s account launch date is <strong>days ago less than or equal to</strong> 0. Then, design your Engagement Studio program. The program starts by sending the welcome email and includes a trigger to check if the customer filed our the form. If the form is filled out, customer will continue to receive the remaining onboarding emails depending on the preference.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-esp.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-27-esp.png\" alt=\"Engagement Studio Program Setup\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n'),
