(1327, 534, '_solution', '<p>For email marketers, receiving real-time feedback is a game-changer because it enables them to measure and improve email performance beyond just A/B testing. By incorporating an email feedback widget in NextData\'s emails, you have added a new dimension to communication, transforming each email from a mere message into a two-way conversation.</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Step-by-step Guide</h5>\r\n\r\n<p><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">1</span> The main concept behind the email feedback magic involves using form handlers and HML to dynamically populate URLs. To begin, you will need to create a new custom field to collect feedback from prospects. You can name the field <strong>Email Feedback</strong> and choose either the text or dropdown field type. If you want to capture multiple responses every time a prospect submits a form handler, make sure to enable the option to <strong>Record and display multiple responses</strong>. For the dropdown field type, you can set the values to <strong>happy</strong>, <strong>neutral</strong>, and <strong>sad</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-custom-field.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-custom-field.png\" alt=\"Creating Custom Field\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n\r\n[guide id=\"114\" status=\"closed\"]\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">2</span> Next, you will need to create a form handler for capturing prospect\'s feedback in the email. When creating a form handler, it is important to also create a success location and an error location page. You can use a simple landing page template from the resources section as a basis for the success page. Pay close attention to a few settings. Ensure that <strong>Enable data forwarding to the success location</strong> is checked and remember the <strong>External Field Name</strong> for the form fields you have added.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-form-handler.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-form-handler.png\" alt=\"Form Handler Setup\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">3</span> Finally, you will generate three URLs using the form handler that you have just created. You will need to add two values to the form handler URL: email address and sentiment. For instance, if you want to create a URL for a <strong>happy</strong> sentiment, your URL might appear as follows:</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-js\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\">https://www.nextinc.xyz/l/761802/2023-10-06/22wdm9?email={{Recipient.Email}}&feedback=happy</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"mt-3\"><span class=\"badge text-bg-secondary\">4</span> Once you have created all three URLs, you can use them to link either to icons or images in your email.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"border rounded-3 p-2 mb-3\"><a data-fslightbox href=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-em-cropped.png\"><img src=\"https://marketingcloud30.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/day-28-em-cropped.png\" alt=\"Email Feedback URLs\" class=\"img-fluid\"/></a></div>\r\n'),
