(1655, 664, '_solution', '<p>Today, you will not only extract data, but also refine and retitle it. Let\'s explore conditional filtering further.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To tackle today\'s challenge, you will learn about aliasing columns with the <code>AS</code> keyword. This allows you to give columns a temporary name for the scope of your query. Additionally, you will use the <code><</code> operator within the <code>WHERE</code> clause to query data that meets a specific condition.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    COUNT(id) AS eligible_customers\r\nFROM [NextMobile Usage]\r\nWHERE \r\n    data_usage < 20\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Choose which columns or calculations to extract.</li>\r\n    <li><code>COUNT</code>: A function to count the number of rows that match a specified condition.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Designate the source table of your data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Set the conditions for the rows you wish to retrieve.</li>\r\n    <li><code><</code>: The less-than operator to filter rows based on a value less than the one specified.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ‚ö°Ô∏è Query Result: <strong>183</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>By quantifying the number of eligible customers, you\'ve provided a valuable metric for NextMobile\'s marketing initiatives. Every challenge you conquer enhances your SQL skills. Onward to Day 4!</p>\r\n'),
