(1732, 669, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 7! Today, you will learn about navigating data ranges in SQL. In this challenge, you will use the <code>BETWEEN</code> operator in conjunction with <code>WHERE</code> to identify customers who fall within the targeted data usage range.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id,\r\n    data_usage,\r\n    data_plan\r\nFROM [NextMobile Usage]\r\nWHERE \r\n    data_usage / data_plan BETWEEN 0.5 AND 0.75\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Specifies the columns to include in the result.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Indicates the table that contains the data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Applies conditions to filter the data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>BETWEEN</code>: An operator used to define a specific interval or range for data. It is also equivalent to the expression that uses the greater than or equal to (>=) and less than or equal to (<=) operators. For example: A >= low AND A <= high.\r\n        <ul>\r\n            <li>For today\'s challenge, the goal is to find customers who have used 50% to 75% of their data plan. The calculation <code>data_usage / data_plan</code> dynamically computes the usage percentage for each customer.</li>\r\n        </ul>\r\n    </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ‚ö° Query Result: <strong>299</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Great job! By using the <code>BETWEEN</code> and <code>WHERE</code> functions, you have identified customers eligible for a targeted campaign. This ensures that the offers resonate well with their usage patterns. Stay curious and look forward to more SQL tips as we continue our 30-day challenge!</p>\r\n'),
