(1770, 671, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 9! Today we will learn about SQL and how to use the <code>LIKE</code> operator. This operator helps us find specific roles in our business accounts, such as administrators, accountants, and others. With <code>LIKE</code>, we can filter data efficiently and accurately.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id,\r\n    email,\r\n    role\r\nFROM [NextMobile Commercial]\r\nWHERE\r\n    role LIKE \'%administrator%\'\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Choose the columns to be displayed in your query result.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Indicate the source table for your data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Set the conditions for data filtering.</li>\r\n    <li><code>LIKE</code>: An operator that allows for pattern matching in character data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ‚ö° Query Result: <strong>373</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Great job! By using the <code>LIKE</code> operator, you have successfully identified the administrators in NextMobile\'s business customer base. This approach is important for finding specific audiences. Keep an eye out for more SQL challenges that will further improve your data analysis skills!</p>\r\n'),
