(1790, 672, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 10! Missing data can provide valuable information, and that\'s where the <code>IS NULL</code> condition comes in. By combining it with the pattern-matching capabilities of the <code>LIKE</code> operator, you can investigate both the present and the absent data in your dataset.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id,\r\n    email,\r\n    role,\r\n    phone\r\nFROM [NextMobile Commercial]\r\nWHERE\r\n    role LIKE \'%administrator%\' AND phone IS NULL\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Operators Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Choose the columns to be displayed in your query result.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Indicate the source table for your data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Set the conditions for data filtering.</li>\r\n    <li><code>LIKE</code>: An operator that allows for pattern matching in character data.</li>\r\n    <li><code>IS NULL</code>: Use this condition to pinpoint missing or absent data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    ‚ö° Query Result: <strong>79</strong>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>By combining pattern searching with missing data detection, you can ensure that databases are comprehensive and up-to-date. Let\'s continue with more SQL quests!</p>\r\n'),
