(1877, 680, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 14! Sometimes, data isn\'t just about what it is, but also about what it could be under certain conditions. The <code>CASE</code> statement allows you to define those conditions and determine outputs accordingly. Whether you\'re categorizing data, creating new labels, or redefining existing values based on conditions, today is all about shaping your results dynamically. So, let\'s explore the world of \"if this, then that\"!</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT id, data_usage,\r\nCASE \r\n    WHEN data_usage > 50 THEN \'Heavy\'\r\n    WHEN data_usage > 25 THEN \'Moderate\'\r\n    ELSE \'Light\'\r\nEND AS user_type\r\nFROM [NextMobile Usage]\r\nWHERE \r\n    data_usage != 0\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Pick columns for the output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>CASE/WHEN/THEN</code>: Use this statement for conditional logic within queries.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Point to the relevant table.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Apply conditions to hone in on specific data.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result:</strong> 943 rows\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Excellent! You have skillfully classified your customers using the <code>CASE</code> statement, which sets the stage for more personalized marketing efforts. Let\'s continue with more SQL explorations!</p>'),
