(2103, 708, '_solution', '<p>On day 20, your task is to identify the NextMobile customers who are approaching their service renewal date. The SQL query you create is vital for NextMobile\'s targeted campaign. This ensures that timely offers are presented to customers as they approach their renewal date.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    id, \r\n    launch_date,\r\n    DATEADD(YEAR, DATEDIFF(YEAR, launch_date, GETDATE()), launch_date) AS renewal_date\r\nFROM \r\n    [NextMobile Users]\r\nWHERE\r\n    DATEDIFF(DAY, GETDATE(), DATEADD(YEAR, DATEDIFF(YEAR, launch_date, GETDATE()), launch_date)) BETWEEN 0 AND 30\r\n    AND DATEADD(YEAR, DATEDIFF(YEAR, launch_date, GETDATE()), launch_date) &gt; GETDATE()\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Initiates the query to fetch user data based on the specified criteria.</li>\r\n    <li><code>DATEADD</code>: Adds a specified time interval to a date. Here, it\'s used to calculate the annual renewal date from the launch date.</li>\r\n    <li><code>DATEDIFF</code>: Determines the difference between two dates. You\'ll use it to calculate how many years have passed since the initial launch date and to project the next renewal date.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Sets the conditions for selecting rows. In this scenario, you\'re filtering for customers whose renewal date falls within the next 30 days.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GETDATE()</code>: Retrieves the current system date and time, which is crucial for identifying current renewals.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result:</strong> 79 (as of 2024-02-25)\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Great job! By correctly applying these functions, you\'ve allowed NextMobile to engage with customers on time for their renewals. This fosters positive customer relationships and ensures continuity in service. Keep practicing and refining these skills as we continue with the SQL30 challenge!</p>\r\n'),
