(2164, 711, '_solution', '<p>Today\'s focus is on the <code>LEFT JOIN</code> command in SQL and how it can greatly improve the data integration process. It enables the seamless combination of survey data with customer details, ensuring that no customer is left out, including those who didn\'t respond. This method provides a comprehensive view of our survey outreach.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    s.id, \r\n    s.first_name, \r\n    s.last_name, \r\n    s.email,\r\n    sr.nps_score\r\nFROM [NextMobile Survey] s\r\nLEFT JOIN [NextMobile Survey Responses] sr \r\n    ON s.id = sr.id\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Chooses columns to include in the query result.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM [NextMobile Survey] s</code>: Identifies the primary table for the query, with \'s\' as an alias.</li>\r\n    <li><code>LEFT JOIN [NextMobile Survey Responses] sr</code>: Merges data from the survey responses into the query, with \'sr\' as an alias, ensuring all survey recipients are included, regardless of response status.</li>\r\n    <li><code>ON s.id = sr.id</code>: Specifies the condition for the join, linking records based on matching IDs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result:</strong> 97 rows\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>By learning <code>LEFT JOIN</code>, you can manage more complicated data links, which helps make your data more useful. Keep practicing, these skills are very useful for anyone working with data.</p>\r\n'),
