(2183, 713, '_solution', '<p>Day 24\'s task is about using SQL to combine different sets of data for better analysis. You\'ll work with two sets of survey data: one from the Marketing team and another from the Sales team. The goal is to bring together all customer feedback to better understand their experience. By using <code>UNION</code>, the surveys from both teams can be easily mixed.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT\r\n    id,\r\n    nps_score\r\nFROM\r\n    [NextMobile Survey Responses]\r\nUNION\r\nSELECT\r\n    id,\r\n    nps_score\r\nFROM\r\n    [NextMobile Survey Responses_Sales]\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Picks specific columns to be included in the output.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Identifies the source table for the query.</li>\r\n    <li><code>UNION</code>: Combines results from multiple <code>SELECT</code> statements into a single result set, removing duplicates.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result:</strong> 72 rows\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>Learning the <code>UNION</code> operator helps you merge similar datasets. This is important in data analysis and reporting. Merging data improves the insights you can get from it and shows how versatile and efficient SQL is for managing data. As we continue the last six days of our SQL30 challenge, your skill in data merging will be helpful.</p>\r\n'),
