(2202, 714, '_solution', '<p>Welcome to Day 25! Today, you\'re creating a mailing list for the loyalty program using a subquery. Think of it like a two-step process. The main query collects basic customer data from the \'NextMobile Users\' table. The subquery goes into the \'NextMobile Orders_2023\' table to find customers who spend a lot. When the subquery finds those high spenders, the main query filters the customer data to give the right audience for the loyalty program.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT \r\n    u.id, \r\n    u.first_name,\r\n    u.last_name, \r\n    u.email\r\nFROM [NextMobile Users] u\r\nWHERE u.id IN (\r\n    SELECT \r\n        customer_id AS id\r\n    FROM [NextMobile Orders_2023]\r\n    GROUP BY customer_id\r\n    HAVING SUM(amount) &gt; 10000\r\n)\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><strong>Outer Query</strong>: The main query selects customer details (id, first_name, last_name, email) from <code>[NextMobile Users]</code>.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>Subquery</strong>: The nested query identifies customers who have spent more than 10000 within <code>[NextMobile Orders_2023]</code>.</li>\r\n    <li><strong>WHERE u.id IN ()</strong>: This condition filters the outer query, selecting only the customers identified in the subquery results.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result:</strong> 180 rows\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>You\'re making excellent progress with your SQL skills, and this loyalty program challenge shows how they have real-world applications! With only 5 days left in our SQL30 journey, keep the momentum going and get ready to tackle even more exciting marketing scenarios.</p>\r\n'),
