(2221, 715, '_solution', '<p>On Day 26, you\'ll prepare data to help the marketing team understand the distribution of orders. This involves using a subquery to create a temporary dataset, then counting the number of orders sent to each state. This can be achieved by using subqueries in the <code>FROM</code> clause. The objective is to produce a detailed list of orders dispatched to each state in 2023.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n<code class=\"language-sql\">\r\nSELECT o.state, COUNT(o.order_id) AS order_count\r\nFROM (\r\n    SELECT o.order_id, u.state\r\n    FROM [NextMobile Orders_2023] o\r\n    JOIN [NextMobile Users] u \r\n        ON o.customer_id = u.id\r\n    WHERE o.status = \'shipped\'\r\n) AS o\r\nGROUP BY o.state\r\n</code>\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5 class=\"mt-4\">SQL Queries and Functions Used</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li><code>SELECT</code>: Initiates the query, focusing on the state and the count of orders for each.</li>\r\n    <li><code>FROM</code>: Includes a <strong>subquery</strong> to pre-process data, creating a temporary table <code>o</code> that combines order IDs with their corresponding state.</li>\r\n    <li>Subquery within <code>FROM</code> clause: This nested query joins the orders and users tables to align each shipped order with its state, filtering by \'shipped\' status.</li>\r\n    <li><code>JOIN</code>: Links <code>NextMobile Orders_2023</code> with <code>NextMobile Users</code> based on the customer ID, ensuring each order is associated with the correct state.</li>\r\n    <li><code>WHERE</code>: Filters the orders in the subquery to include only those with a \'shipped\' status.</li>\r\n    <li><code>GROUP BY</code>: Aggregates the results by state, which is crucial for calculating the total number of orders per state.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<aside class=\"bg-light-subtle p-4 my-3 rounded-3 border border-light-subtle\" role=\"alert\">\r\n    üí° <strong>Query Result</strong>\r\n    <table class=\"table\">\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <th>State</th>\r\n            <th>Order Count</th>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>AZ</td>\r\n            <td>80</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>CA</td>\r\n            <td>277</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>FL</td>\r\n            <td>234</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>NY</td>\r\n            <td>149</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>OR</td>\r\n            <td>20</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n        <tr>\r\n            <td>WA</td>\r\n            <td>48</td>\r\n        </tr>\r\n    </table>\r\n</aside>\r\n\r\n<p>With SQL, you can shape data to answer critical business questions. This analysis will help guide the marketing team\'s budget decisions. Get ready, the last few days of SQL30 will focus on email marketing!</p>\r\n'),
